The Ichthys, also known as the Fish, is an ancient Christian symbol that has deep roots in early Christian history. The symbol consists of two intersecting arcs that resemble the profile of a fish. Often, the Greek letters ΙΧΘΥΣ (Ichthys) are written inside the fish shape.

The Greek word ΙΧΘΥΣ stands for “Jesus Christ, Son of God, Savior.” Each letter represents the first letter of the Greek words Iesous Christos Theou Huios Sotor.
This acronym encapsulates the core beliefs of Christianity, making the Ichthys a powerful declaration of faith.
During times of persecution, Christians used the fish symbol to identify themselves to one another and to mark safe meeting places. This simple yet profound symbol provided a way for early Christians to express their faith covertly.

The fish is associated with water, which is central to the sacrament of baptism. This connection reinforces the idea of spiritual rebirth and purification through Christ.
As Jesus said, “Follow me, and I will make you fishers of men” (Matthew 4:19). The Ichthys encapsulates this call to discipleship and continues to inspire Christians to live out their faith with courage and conviction.
